 Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called with Old English <i>bere</i> or <i>bær</i> ‘barley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, i.e. an outlying grange. Compare   Barwick  . The name is also found in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Bartún</b>.","Polish (<b>Bartoń</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Bartoň</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bartłomiej</i>, Czech <i>Bartoloměj</i>, Slovak <i>Bartolomej</i>, from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Barton was born in 1320, in Baylham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert de Barton, was 25 and her mother, Margaret Goode, was 17. She married William de Burnaville I. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1344, in her hometown, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1320–1344":"1320–1344","1312–1344":"1312–1344","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","1303":"1303","about 1319":"umbes 1319","1312":"1312","1344":"1344","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1320–1344":"1320–1344","1312–1344":"1312–1344","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1303–Female":"1303–Kuollut","1303":"1303","about 1319":"noin 1319","1312":"1312","1344":"1344","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","about 1340":"noin 1340","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1320–1344":"1320–1344","1312–1344":"1312–1344","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","1295–Male":"1295–Décédé","1303–Female":"1303–Décédée","1303":"1303","about 1319":"environ 1319","1312":"1312","1344":"1344","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","about 1340":"environ 1340","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Alice de Barton est née en 1320, à Baylham, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Robert de Barton, avait 25 ans et sa mère, Margaret Goode, avait 17 ans. Elle a épousé William de Burna